1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:03,180
Let's see how to implement a transformer block.

2

00:00:03,180  -->  00:00:06,080
We've already implemented the attention block,

3

00:00:06,080  -->  00:00:07,720
and now as you recall,

4

00:00:07,720  -->  00:00:12,225
we now need to implement the feed-forward part of this block.

5

00:00:12,225  -->  00:00:14,180
Once we have both of these blocks,

6

00:00:14,180  -->  00:00:15,940
we can combine them together.

7

00:00:15,940  -->  00:00:17,940
To define a feed-forward block,

8

00:00:17,940  -->  00:00:22,700
we need to define a new class and inherit from the nn module type.

9

00:00:22,700  -->  00:00:26,340
In this module, we define a sequence of linear layers.

10

00:00:26,340  -->  00:00:32,800
First, we have a linear layer that projects the input dimension to four times its size.

11

00:00:32,800  -->  00:00:35,195
We then have the activation function.

12

00:00:35,195  -->  00:00:42,420
We then have another linear layer that projects the dimension back to the original size.

13

00:00:42,420  -->  00:00:46,490
Then we add the dropout layer to prevent overfitting,

14

00:00:46,490  -->  00:00:48,750
which I've included in this class.

15

00:00:48,750  -->  00:00:51,990
All we need to do in the forward method is to pass

16

00:00:51,990  -->  00:00:55,710
the input through all the linear layers we've just defined.

17

00:00:55,710  -->  00:00:57,490
Now, let's run a quick test.

18

00:00:57,490  -->  00:01:00,640
We will create an instance of the feed-forward block.

19

00:01:00,640  -->  00:01:04,030
We will create a random input of the same size we've done

20

00:01:04,030  -->  00:01:07,490
before and we will pass this input through this block.

21

00:01:07,490  -->  00:01:09,950
If the print is the shape of the output,

22

00:01:09,950  -->  00:01:12,010
it looks just as we expected.

23

00:01:12,010  -->  00:01:13,850
It contains the batch size,

24

00:01:13,850  -->  00:01:15,390
the context window size,

25

00:01:15,390  -->  00:01:18,230
and the dimensionality of our embedding vectors.

26

00:01:18,230  -->  00:01:21,890
Now having the feed-forward block and the multi-head attention block,

27

00:01:21,890  -->  00:01:25,870
we can finally implement the transformer block, and to implement it,

28

00:01:25,870  -->  00:01:30,550
I'll define the class called the block that will again inherit from the module class.

29

00:01:30,550  -->  00:01:33,770
To implement it, I'll need to use the multi-head attention we've just

30

00:01:33,770  -->  00:01:37,630
defined and the feed-forward block we've implemented in this demo.

31

00:01:37,630  -->  00:01:42,760
We also need to add two normalization layers that we will use in this block.

32

00:01:42,760  -->  00:01:44,880
In the forward method of this block,

33

00:01:44,880  -->  00:01:49,640
we first normalize the input and we pass it through the multi-head attention layer.

34

00:01:49,640  -->  00:01:53,820
We then add the original input to the output of the attention layer.

35

00:01:53,820  -->  00:01:58,300
We then normalize this result and pass it to the feed-forward block.

36

00:01:58,300  -->  00:02:02,280
Then we implement another residual connection when we add the output

37

00:02:02,280  -->  00:02:06,330
of this block to the output of the feed-forward block. That's it.

38

00:02:06,330  -->  00:02:09,960
Now let's try to pass some test data through

39

00:02:09,960  -->  00:02:15,090
this transformer block and see if the dimensions of the outputs are still correct.

40

00:02:15,090  -->  00:02:17,640
We create an instance of a transformer block.

41

00:02:17,640  -->  00:02:21,200
We again create a test input of the same size as before.

42

00:02:21,200  -->  00:02:23,980
We pass the input through the transformer block,

43

00:02:23,980  -->  00:02:25,900
and then we look at the shape of the output,

44

00:02:25,900  -->  00:02:28,760
which is exactly what we've expected.
